<span class="displaytext"><b>arlington, va -- </b>u.s. senator (candidate full)'s presidential campaign today released its latest television ad, entitled "broken." the ad highlights (candidate full)'s record of taking on the special interests in washington. the ad will air in key states. <p><b>view the ad here:</b> <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yljkmmr8fek">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yljkmmr8fek</a> </p><p><b><u>script for "broken" (tv :60)</u></b> </p><p><b><i>anncr: </i></b><i>washington's broken. (candidate full) knows it. we're worse off than we were four years ago. </i> </p><p><i>only (candidate last) has taken on big tobacco, drug companies, fought corruption in both parties. he'll reform wall street, battle big oil, make america prosper again. </i></p><p>he's the original maverick. </p><p><i>one is ready to lead -- (candidate last).</i> </p><p><b><i>(candidate full): </i></b><i>i'm (candidate full) and i approved this message.</i> </p><p><b><u>ad facts: script for "broken" (tv :60)</u></b> </p><p><b><i>anncr: </i></b><i>washington's broken. (candidate full) knows it. we're worse off than we were four years ago. only (candidate last) has taken on big tobacco, drug companies, fought corruption in both parties. </i> </p><p><b><i>the new york times</i>' david brooks: "(candidate last) has fought one battle after another against lobbyists and special interests." </b>(david brooks, op-ed, "the real (candidate last)," <i>the new york times</i>, 2/26/08) </p><p><b>public citizen's joan claybrook:</b> "(candidate full) has fought for 14 long, hard years for reforms that seriously limit lobbyists' power ... he has fought for campaign finance reform, limits on gifts and travel from lobbyists, and extensive public disclosure of lobbyists' activities all of which limit the influence of lobbyists and the companies that hire lobbyists in washington, d.c." (public citizen, "one thing overlooked in flap over (candidate last) and lobbyists: his record on reform," press release, 2/26/08) </p><p><b><i>the boston globe</i>: "(candidate last) took on the tobacco industry." </b>"ten years ago, senator (candidate full) took on the tobacco industry, saying he would never back down from legislation to regulate the industry. ... (candidate last)'s decade of work on tobacco, one of the most significant efforts of his congressional career, has earned him enmity from the industry and from some fellow (PARTY NAME)s over the years." (michael kranish, "(candidate last)'s stand on tobacco is put to test," <i>the boston globe</i>, 3/26/08) </p><p><b>(candidate last)'s championing of anti-smoking legislation "faced furious opposition from the tobacco lobby." </b>"in 1998, (candidate last) championed anti-smoking legislation that faced furious opposition from the tobacco lobby. (candidate last) guided the legislation through the senate commerce committee on a 19-1 vote, but then the tobacco companies struck back. they hired 200 lobbyists and spent $40 million in advertising (three times as much as the harry and louise health care reform ads). many of the ads attacked (candidate last) by name, accusing him of becoming a big government liberal. after weeks of bitter debate, the bill died on the senate floor." (david brooks, op-ed, "the real (candidate last)," <i>the new york times</i>, 2/26/08) </p><p><b>in 2004, (candidate full) co-sponsored bipartisan drug reimportation legislation. </b>"at a press conference today, sen. olympia j. snowe (r-maine) introduced breakthrough bipartisan, consensus prescription drug reimportation legislation, the pharmaceutical market access and drug safety act, with sens. byron dorgan (d-nd), (candidate full) (r-az), ted kennedy (d-ma), tom daschle (d-sd), trent lott (r-ms) and debbie stabenow (d-mi)." (sen. olympia snowe, press release, 4/21/04) </p><p><b>(candidate full) fought to allow the importation of cheaper drugs which was "adamantly opposed by industry lobbyists." </b>"(candidate last) said he wanted the government to be able to negotiate lower drug prices and import cheaper drugs from canada, both ideas that were adamantly opposed by industry lobbyists, and which ultimately failed." (eamon javers, "is (candidate full) good for business?" <i>business week online</i>, 2/7/08) </p><p><b>a (candidate full) bill to make it easier for cheap generic drugs to come onto the market drew "strong opposition from the pharmaceutical industry." </b>"the most public front was active last week, with the senate passing a bill intended to make it easier for cheap generic drugs to come onto the market. the bill, sponsored by sens. charles schumer, d-n.y., and (candidate full), r-ariz., drew considerable support in congress and strong opposition from the pharmaceutical industry." ("insurers' 'counter' attacks aim to boost generic drugs," <i>grand rapid press</i>, 8/11/02) </p><p><b>(candidate last) passed campaign finance reform which "was a direct assault on lobbyist power." </b>"in 2002, (candidate last) capped his long push for campaign finance reform by passing the (candidate last)-feingold act. people can argue about the effectiveness of the act, but one thing is beyond dispute. it was a direct assault on lobbyist power, and earned (candidate last) undying enmity among many important parts of the (PARTY NAME) coalition, who felt their soft money influence was being diminished." (david brooks, op-ed, "the real (candidate last)," <i>the new york times</i>, 2/26/08) </p><p><b>(candidate full)'s investigation into the boeing tanker deal "exposed billions of dollars of waste and layers of contracting irregularity." </b>"in 2004, (candidate last) launched a frontal assault on the leasing contract the pentagon had signed with boeing for aerial refueling tankers. (candidate last)'s investigation exposed billions of dollars of waste and layers of contracting irregularity." (david brooks, op-ed, "the real (candidate last)," <i>the new york times</i>, 2/26/08) </p><p><b>(candidate full) led the congressional investigation into jack abramoff. </b>"in 2005, (candidate last) led the congressional investigation into the behavior of the lobbyist jack abramoff. the investigation was exceedingly unpleasant for (PARTY NAME)s, because it exposed shocking misbehavior by important conservative activists." (david brooks, op-ed, "the real (candidate last)," <i>the new york times</i>, 2/26/08) </p><p><b><i>anncr: </i></b><i>he'll reform wall street, battle big oil, make america prosper again. he's the original maverick. one is ready to lead -- (candidate last). <b>(candidate full):</b> i'm (candidate full) and i approved this message.</i> </p><p><b>(candidate full) will be vigilant in holding corporate abuses to account. </b>"americans are right to be offended when extravagant ceo salaries and severance deals bear no relation to their company's success or shareholders' wishes. as president, (candidate full) will see that wrongdoing of this kind is called to account by federal prosecutors. under his reforms, all aspects of a ceo's pay, including severance arrangements, must be approved by shareholders." ((candidate full) 2008, "a leader we can believe in to help small businesses," press release, 6/11/08) </p><p><b>(candidate full) has called for the immediate formation of a justice department mortgage abuse task force. </b>"the task force will aggressively investigate potential criminal wrongdoing in the mortgage industry and bring to justice any who violated the law. the doj task force will offer assistance to state attorney generals who are investigating abusive lending practices." ((candidate full) 2008, "(candidate full)'s economic plan," press release, 4/15/08) </p><p><b>(candidate full) believes we must understand the role speculation is playing in our soaring energy prices. </b>"congress already has several investigations underway to examine this kind of wagering in our energy markets, unrelated to any kind of productive commerce, because it can distort the market, drive prices beyond rational limits, and put the investments and pensions of millions of americans at risk. (candidate full) believes that where we find abuses, they need to be swiftly punished. to make sure it never happens again, we must reform the laws and regulations governing the oil futures market, so that they are just as clear and effective as the rules applied to stocks, bonds, and other financial instruments." ((candidate full) 2008, "securing our energy future," press release, 6/17/08) </p><p><b>(candidate full) voted against the 2005 energy bill.</b> (h.r. 6, cq vote #152: motion agreed to 92-4: r 53-1; d 38-3; i 1-0, 6/23/05, (candidate last) voted nay; h.r. 6, cq vote #158: passed 85-12: r 49-5; d 35-7; i 1-0, 6/28/05, (candidate last) voted nay; h.r. 6, cq vote #213: adopted 74-26: r 49-6; d 25-19; i 0-1, 7/29/05, (candidate last) voted nay) </p><p><b>(candidate full) criticized the 2005 energy bill's "handouts to big business and oil companies," calling them irresponsible.</b> (candidate last): "this bill does little to address the immediate energy crisis we face in this country. the handouts to big business and oil companies are irresponsible and will be disastrous for people of arizona. i cannot in good conscience, vote to pass legislation that does not adequately address issues related to energy efficiency, security, and energy independence." (sen. (candidate full), "(candidate last), kyl say no to flawed energy bill," press release, 6/28/05) </p><p><b>(candidate full) has proposed a comprehensive "jobs for america" economic plan to make our country prosperous again: <a href="http://www.(candidate full).com/economicbriefing/">http://www.(candidate full).com/economicbriefing/</a></b></p></span>



